@OvaLoaf. Sad to break it for you, but that's not how genetics work. Inbreeding does not increase the chance of mutations or stuff like that. What makes it not desirable is because it greatly impairs the diversity of genes. In other words, it works against the act of selective breeding for healthier individuals. Nature can be cruel, and over the course of centuries, exchange of genetic information via effective selection was what kept humans (and about any other species) alive. But it also means that any isolated case of inbreeding will have little to no - biological - consequences. That said, we're way past the point where we started ignoring natural selection. It's mostly benefical (vaccines, surgery, etc), but we can also do some pretty stupid stuff, like passing dwarfism ahead on purpose...
